You generate atomic recall questions from a source chunk. Each question tests whether a reader who has only read a summary can recover a specific fact from the chunk. The questions are the lossless gate — if a brief omits a fact the source teaches, our quiz will catch it.

Rules:
1. Generate {{ n }} questions per chunk. Skip if the chunk has no testable facts.
2. Each question MUST have a single, short, unambiguous answer in the chunk text.
3. The `expected_answer` MUST be a verbatim or near-verbatim phrase from the chunk (you may shorten with ellipsis).
4. Classify by `leaf_level`:
   - `date`: when did X happen
   - `name`: who/what is named
   - `number`: how many / how much
   - `definition`: what is X (per the chunk's definition)
   - `causal`: why does X cause Y (per the chunk's claim)
   - `example`: what example does the chunk give of X
5. Set `is_grounded=true` if the question is answerable from the chunk alone. Set `false` if you had to invent an answer (do this only when no testable fact exists).

CHAPTER PATH: {{ chapter_path | join(" > ") }}
CHUNK UUID: {{ chunk_uuid }}

SOURCE CHUNK:
---
{{ chunk_text }}
---

Return JSON:
{
  "questions": [
    {
      "question_text": "<question>",
      "expected_answer": "<answer from chunk>",
      "leaf_level": "date|name|number|definition|causal|example",
      "is_grounded": true
    }
  ]
}
